userStories.notes:
Bug location: platform/mcp-server/src/reload.ts, line 126-133, in the pruneStaleState function.

Current code:
```typescript
const prevSessionPermissionsLength = state.sessionPermissions.length;
state.sessionPermissions = state.sessionPermissions.filter(
  rule => rule.tool === null || state.registry.toolLookup.has(rule.tool),
);
```

The problem: state.registry.toolLookup only contains plugin tools (prefixed as plugin_tool, e.g., 'slack_send_message'). Browser tool names (e.g., 'browser_execute_script', 'browser_get_cookies') are never added to toolLookup (see platform/mcp-server/src/registry.ts:96-131 — buildRegistry only iterates over plugin tools). So this filter drops ALL browser tool session permission rules on every reload.

Fix: Build a set of valid browser tool names from state.cachedBrowserTools and include them in the filter condition:
```typescript
const validBrowserToolNames = new Set(state.cachedBrowserTools.map(c => c.name));
const prevSessionPermissionsLength = state.sessionPermissions.length;
state.sessionPermissions = state.sessionPermissions.filter(
  rule => rule.tool === null || state.registry.toolLookup.has(rule.tool) || validBrowserToolNames.has(rule.tool),
);
```

Note: state.cachedBrowserTools is already populated before pruneStaleState is called — it's set at platform/mcp-server/src/reload.ts:254 (the atomic swap), and pruneStaleState is called at line 257.

Test file: platform/mcp-server/src/reload.test.ts. The existing test at lines 266-285 tests plugin tool pruning but does NOT include a browser tool session permission rule. Add a new test (or extend the existing test) that adds a browser tool rule (e.g., { tool: 'browser_execute_script', domain: 'example.com', scope: 'tool_domain' }) to state.sessionPermissions before reload and verifies it survives.

Note: The test setup may need to ensure state.cachedBrowserTools is populated. The performReload function calls rebuildCachedBrowserTools which populates this from state.browserTools. The default createState() initializes browserTools as an empty array and cachedBrowserTools as an empty array. Either: (a) manually set state.cachedBrowserTools to include a browser_execute_script entry before the reload, or (b) let performReload populate it naturally (it updates state.browserTools from the fresh import at line 411). Approach (b) is more realistic — state.browserTools is set to the imported browserTools array at line 411, which includes browser_execute_script.
